post_text:
The World Autism Awareness Shirts have been distributed! Thank you for once again making this a huge success to raise awareness for our special students!

Faculty and staff, your shirts are in your mailboxes at your respective schools.

Students at Honesdale High School and Stourbridge Primary Center: Your shirt(s) will be in with your belongings that you are picking up during the end of this week.

Students at Preston and Damascus: You may pick up your shirt(s) during lunch pick up hours on Monday, Wednesday, or Friday from 11am - 1pm at your respective school.

Students at Wayne Highlands Middle School and Lakeside Elementary: Please contact your principal to set up a time to pick up your shirt(s). You may email Mr. Jordan at pjordan@whsdk12.com for the middle school and Mrs. Rickard at srickard@whsdk12.com for Lakeside.

If you have any questions, concerns, or problems with your order, please reach out to Mrs. Gearhart at mgearhart@whsdk12.com. Thank you!

post_text:
How to submit to 95.3 and Classic Hit 105.3's Radio Yearbook
1. All audio needs to be no more than 50 seconds. Each senior message should consist of Name, Age, School, interests in school...ie fields of study, sports, music, art and what their plans are for the future.
2. The audio needs to be recorded on Facebook messenger and sent to George Schmitt. To do this, press on the blue microphone on the left hand bottom side to record your message. You do need to have Facebook Messenger downloaded to submit audio.
3. We will start airing these in May on both Classic Hits 105.3 and 95.3DNH weekdays between 6am and 6pm.
For questions, please email Emily Grillo at egrillo@boldgoldmedia.com

post_text:
Tech Ed teachers trying to lend a helping hand!

Recently, Matt Rickard was reached out to by personnel at Wayne Memorial Hospital. He was asked if his department could make something to aid their staff in this critical time. Going off a recent article published by Devon Chang illustrating a "Aerosol Box" created by Dr. Hsien Yung Lai and being implemented in hospitals in other countries to help hospital staff. Matt Rickard reached out to Joe Mang, knowing his experience with the robotics team and working with similar fabrication and materials. Mr. Mang immediately contacted senior Ryan Forelli captain of his robotics team to assist in drawing the item and getting accurate dimensions. The following day Mr. Mang and Mr. Rickard used drawings made by Ryan and created two working prototypes given to Wayne Memorial Hospital. Since then, St. Luke's Hospital and other healthcare providers are interested in having such items made.

https://photos.app.goo.gl/TD9jTmsQ5rAPBTqe7

text:
Tech Ed teachers trying to lend a helping hand!

Recently, Matt Rickard was reached out to by personnel at Wayne Memorial Hospital. He was asked if his department could make something to aid their staff in this critical time. Going off a recent article published by Devon Chang illustrating a "Aerosol Box" created by Dr. Hsien Yung Lai and being implemented in hospitals in other countries to help hospital staff. Matt Rickard reached out to Joe Mang, knowing his experience with the robotics team and working with similar fabrication and materials. Mr. Mang immediately contacted senior Ryan Forelli captain of his robotics team to assist in drawing the item and getting accurate dimensions. The following day Mr. Mang and Mr. Rickard used drawings made by Ryan and created two working prototypes given to Wayne Memorial Hospital. Since then, St. Luke's Hospital and other healthcare providers are interested in having such items made.

It is reported that the Wolf Administration will continue to monitor COVID-19 Virus in the Commonwealth, and at the end of the 10 days, will reevaluate and decide whether continued closure is needed. Please visit our website https://www.whsd12.com for additional information from the Wayne Highlands School District and Governor Wolf in the days ahead.

WAYNE HIGHLANDS SCHOOL DISTRICT KINDERGARTEN REGISTRATION

HONESDALE-PRESTON-DAMASCUS AREAS
In order to plan out kindergarten program for the 2020-2021 school year, we must know with considerable accuracy the number of children who will be enrolled.

Kindergarten enrollment is restricted to children who will be five years of age before September 1, 2020.

If you have a preschool child who may be eligible to attend kindergarten, please call the school in your area as soon as possible.

The telephone numbers are as follows:

Honesdale Area: Stourbridge Primary – (570) 253-3010
Damascus Area: Damascus School – (570) 224-4114
Preston Area: Preston School – (570) 798-2516

post_text: The Honesdale High School Alumni Association was pleased to present Victoria Wormuth with a Summer Grant for 2019. Victoria is going into her senior year at HHS. Throughout high school, Victoria has participated in chamber choir 9th - 11th grade. She participated in District Chorus in grades 10 and 11. She was a cast member in the HHS musical "Beauty and the Beast" in her junior year. Victoria participated in the Marywood Wind Band Celebration in the 9th and 10th grades. She is a member of the National Honor Society. Through this grant, the Honesdale High School Alumni Association is thrilled to be able to cover the costs for Victoria to attend The Choral Academy at Mansfield University from Sunday, July 21 to Saturday, July 27, 2019.

She is a member of the National Honor Society. Through this grant, the Honesdale High School Alumni Association is thrilled to be able to cover the costs for Victoria to attend The Choral Academy at Mansfield University from Sunday, July 21 to Saturday, July 27, 2019.

post_text: Congratulations to sophomore, Ella Sherman! Ella has auditioned and advanced from District 9 Chorus, to Region 4 Chorus, and last week to the Pennsylvania All-State Choir. Ella is the first person from Honesdale High School to make it to the All-State level for Chorus in the past five years. She will be traveling to Pittsburg, PA on April 3-6, 2019 to join 160 top vocalists from across the state.

post_text:
The Wayne Highlands Middle School Science Olympiad team competed Saturday against 60 teams from 6 states at the Baynard Rustin Science Olympiad Invitational near West Chester PA. The team consists of 15 members in 7th through 9th grade and has 3 high school assistant coaches. The Zack Wilken and John Rodriguez took home a 2nd place medal in Mystery Architecture.
Additional successes include: John Rodriguez and Zack Wilken placed 13th in Road Scholar, Soren Schacter and Griffin Rogers placed 14th in Potions and Poisons, and J.P. Ahern and Michaela Breidenstein placed 18th in Roller Coaster. The team heads to the Little Tiger Invitational at Northwestern Lehigh High School in February. Great job and Good Luck Hornets!!

post_text:
It’s National School Lunch Week!

Did you know that Pennsylvania served more than 167 million school lunches last year? These nutritious meals help students fuel their minds and succeed in the classroom.

Food insecurity impacts communities across the commonwealth. Free and reduced-price lunches provide a dependable and consistent source of nutrition to students, which helps improve their overall health and well-being.

Please join us in recognizing the importance of school lunch programs across Pennsylvania – this week and every week.

post_text: HHS Wins Keystone Energy Efficiency Alliance Award! Honesdale High School came in first place as one of only four schools in the Commonwealth to earn the Moving To The Head Of The Class Award. The award comes from the Keystone Energy Efficiency Alliance and recognizes the districts that have made the greatest strides towards energy efficiency in the past year. As one of the winning school, HHS will receive money from the Energy Efficiency Alliance to continue making their school both more cost-effective and environmentally friendly.

Friday, April 6, 2018, the Blood Drive Committee at Honesdale High School will be sponsoring our 3rd and final blood drive for the year. This is our last opportunity to achieve our annual goal of collecting over 200 pints of blood! As always, this helps the Red Cross in their nationwide efforts to provide much needed blood components to patients, one pint saves three lives! This also benefits our graduating seniors because as a thank you, the Red Cross will provide $2500 in scholarship award to participating High Schools!
Our blood drive theme this year is My Heart Beats for Others... Donate, Don't Hesitate! We will be honoring the victims of the recent Stoneman Douglas High School Tragedy. Please consider coming out to support our students and humanity!

Google Form for Sign ups: https://goo.gl/forms/WHuk1jAalSkXjajS2
